Plotting the spread of COVID-19 in the Rhône

Plot a line graph showing the number of patients hospitalised (y-axis) over time (x-axis) for the departement number 69 (“Rhône”).

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, hospitalised)) +
    geom_line()

Take the plot from the previous question and change the date breaks and labels to label each month with its full name.

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, hospitalised)) +
    geom_line() +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "month", date_minor_breaks = "month", date_labels = "%B")

Now, we want to compare this to the number of deaths each day. However, the deceased is a total count rather than the new number of deaths. Use the lag function to add a deceased_new variable to the data from département number 69:

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  mutate(deceased_new = deceased - lag(deceased, n = 1))

Now, produce a plot that shows the number of newly deceased people in département 69 over time:

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  mutate(deceased_new = deceased - lag(deceased, n = 1) )%>%
  ggplot(aes(date, deceased_new)) +

This plot is noisy because of the (thankfully) much lower counts. Modify your code from above to produce a plot with a 7 day rolling average:

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  mutate(deceased_new = deceased - lag(deceased, n = 1) )%>%
  mutate(deceased_new_7day = roll_meanl(deceased_new, n = 7) )%>%
  ggplot(aes(date, deceased_new_7day)) +
    geom_line() +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "month", date_minor_breaks = "month", date_labels = "%B")

Days of the Week: Reporting Bias?

Take the covid dataset, group by the date, take the sum (sm_sum) of the variable deceased across all the départements for each day, and add a variable wday giving the day of the week for each row of the data:

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(sm_sum(deceased)) %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE))
## # A tibble: 198 × 3

Starting with your code from the previous question, compute the change in the variable deceased_sum for each, and compute the average number of new deaths by the day of the week:

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(sm_sum(deceased)) %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(deaths = deceased_sum - lag(deceased_sum,n = 1)) %>%
  group_by(wday) %>%
  summarize(sm_mean(deaths))
## # A tibble: 7 × 2
##   wday      deaths_mean

## 6 Saturday         83.4
## 7 Sunday           64.6

More Plotting Practice

For a final plot, pick any département and produce an arrow plot that shows the change in hospitalisation numbers over time. Rather than showing every day, just show the weekly change from Monday to Monday. Color the lines according the direction of the change and try to include a good scale for the x-axis.

covid %>%
  filter(departement == 69) %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date)) %>%
  filter(wday == 1) %>%
  arrange(date) %>%
  mutate(
    hospitalised_1week = lag(hospitalised, n = 1),
    h_delta = hospitalised - hospitalised_1week,
    color = if_else(h_delta > 0, "red", "green")
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, hospitalised_1week)) +
    geom_segment(
      aes(xend = date, yend = hospitalised, color = color),
      arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.02, "npc"))
    ) +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "month", date_labels = "%B") +
    scale_color_identity()

You can change (hopefully easily) the département number and quickly see the changes for another region as well.
